ResumeAI — Database Migrations (Alembic)
==========================================

Why
---
Phase 4 baseline. From this commit forward Alembic is the *only* allowed
mechanism for schema changes. The previous "drop sqlite + restart" pattern
(used during Phase 1-3 dev) is now banned (PROJECT_SPEC §5.7 + ROADMAP §8.5).

Configuration
-------------
* ``backend/alembic.ini``   — Alembic CLI settings; ``sqlalchemy.url`` is
                              overridden at runtime by ``env.py`` (see below).
* ``backend/alembic/env.py`` — pulls the live DB URL from ``app.config`` and
                              registers every model on ``Base.metadata``.
                              SQLite ``ALTER TABLE`` is automatically wrapped
                              in batch mode (``render_as_batch=True``).

The DB URL therefore tracks ``DB_URL`` in ``.env`` (or the default
``sqlite+aiosqlite:///data/resume_assistant.db``). The async ``+aiosqlite``
suffix is stripped because Alembic itself runs synchronously.

Common operations (always run from ``backend/``)
------------------------------------------------
1. **Show current revision**::

       python -m alembic current

2. **Create a new migration after editing models**::

       python -m alembic revision --autogenerate -m "add-foo-column"

   Always review the generated file in ``alembic/versions/``. Autogenerate
   may miss server-side defaults, check constraints, or rename detection —
   adjust manually as needed.

3. **Apply pending migrations** (deployment / upgrade)::

       python -m alembic upgrade head

4. **Roll back one revision** (rarely useful in production but handy in dev)::

       python -m alembic downgrade -1

5. **Stamp existing DB without running migrations** (e.g. when adopting
   Alembic on an already-populated DB; only used once for the baseline)::

       python -m alembic stamp head

Conventions
-----------
* Migration messages: lowercase, hyphenated, imperative
  (e.g. ``add-batch-id-index``, not ``Add Batch Id Index``).
* Never edit a migration after it has been pushed to ``main`` — generate a
  new one instead. Earlier revisions are immutable so production deploys
  produce a deterministic schema.
* SQLite + production: ``render_as_batch`` already covers the
  no-real-ALTER-TABLE limitation. If you ever switch to PostgreSQL, you can
  drop that flag.
* Tests use ``conftest.py::setup_db`` which calls
  ``Base.metadata.create_all`` directly for an ephemeral test DB — they do
  *not* run migrations. The two paths must agree on schema definitions.

Bootstrap a fresh deploy
------------------------
::

    cd backend
    rm -f data/resume_assistant.db          # only on a brand-new install
    python -m alembic upgrade head          # creates every table at HEAD

Then ``uvicorn app.main:app`` will start. The lifespan hook still calls
``Base.metadata.create_all`` as a no-op safety net (creates only tables
missing from metadata, never alters), but the canonical creation path is
``alembic upgrade head``.
